\begin_layout Subsubsection

\color black
Weighting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
This step is entirely dependent on the model of information retrieval used.
 It defines how important a term in a given document.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dah06"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
In general, most term weighting formulas are built by combination of two
 factors.
 A local weighting factor measuring the local representativity of a term
 in the document, and an overall weighting factor measuring the global represent
ativity of a term with respect to the collection of documents
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Amr08"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
That leads to two types : 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\color black
Local weighting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
Local weighting takes into account the local information of the term that
 depend only on the document.
 It is typically a function of frequency of occurrence of the word in the
 document, denoted 
\series bold
tf
\series default
 
