key "Dah06"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

\color black
Querying 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
Querying is the phase of interaction between the system and the user.
 This expresses the need for information via a query language that the system
 will take care of interpreting.
 This interpretation is done according to the query template and is designed
 to understand user needs and express them in a formalism similar to the
 one used when indexing documents.
 This process provides an inner query.
 Following this phase of query interpreting, a matching pattern calculates
 the match between the inner  query and each document in the index.
 This calculation established by the mapping function, has traditionally
 resulted in an ordered list of documents.
 It should, at this level, a semantic comparison (not equal) between concepts
 in of document and those of the query.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
The comparison between query and document rarely leads to strict equivalences,
 but rather to partial equivalences: the document is only part of the query.
 The first document in the list returned by the system is one that is considered
 by the system as the most relevant, that is to say the one that best suits
 the query, again according to the system.
 The final document is one that is considered by the system as the least
 relevant.
 This notion of relevance is based on the proximity between the needs expressed
 by the user and the results provided by the system.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dah06"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\color black
Relevance concept
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
Relevance is a central concept of the query because all evaluations are
 based around this concept.
 But it is also the most poorly understood concept, despite numerous studies
 on this concept as the one in
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Denos97"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
Let us see some definitions of the relevance.
 Relevance is: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\color black
The correspondence between a document and a query, a measure of informativeness
 of the document to the query; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\color black
A degree of relationship (overlap, relativity, ...) between the document and
 the query; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\color black
A degree of surprise that comes with a document that is relevant to the
 needs of the user; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\color black
A measure of usefulness of the document to the user.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
Even in these definitions, the used concepts (informativeness, relativity,
 surprise ...) remains very vague because users have very different needs.
 They have very different criteria for judging whether a document is relevant.
 So the notion of relevance is used to cover a very wide range of criteria
 and relations
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dah06"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

